<div id="review_1170696895" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1170696895" />
    <a title="Richard" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5546147-richard"><img alt="Richard" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1340525485p2/5546147.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1170696895?book_show_action=true">Jan 16, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Richard" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Richard" href="/user/show/5546147-richard">Richard</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5546147-richard?shelf=queer">queer</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5546147-richard?shelf=graphic-novels">graphic-novels</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5546147-richard?shelf=read-in-15">read-in-15</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1170696895" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12915625956942247343">I was in love with Pedro Zamora.<br/><br/>Oh, I never met him. I just watched (and obsessively re-watched) season 3 of The Real World. Pedro was sweet and smart and funny and brave and he had a laugh exactly like my own boyfriend&apos;s. It&apos;s funny now to remember how starved we were then for honest representation. Pedro was that, but also more than that. He was was fantastic. I don&apos;t think I&apos;m crazy, but I really felt like he was my friend.<br/><br/>Naturally, I bought this book when it came out, but then I let it sit </span>
  <span id="freeText12915625956942247343" style="display:none">I was in love with Pedro Zamora.<br /><br />Oh, I never met him. I just watched (and obsessively re-watched) season 3 of The Real World. Pedro was sweet and smart and funny and brave and he had a laugh exactly like my own boyfriend's. It's funny now to remember how starved we were then for honest representation. Pedro was that, but also more than that. He was was fantastic. I don't think I'm crazy, but I really felt like he was my friend.<br /><br />Naturally, I bought this book when it came out, but then I let it sit on a shelf for almost fifteen years. I wanted to read it, sure, but I was in no rush to cry for several hours. And seriously, to this day, I can picture Pedro, hear his voice, his laugh. I didn't need a book to help me remember.<br /><br />Well, Pedro and Me turns out to be a very generous and kind remembrance of a special, very specific friendship. <br /><br />If you've read A Heartbreaking Work of Staggering Genius, you know that Dave Eggers was almost on this season of The Real World, but that Judd Winick eventually won the spot instead. I couldn't help wondering how the story might have been different if Eggers (who I admire) had been chosen for the position. It seems likely that he and Pedro would still have been friends, and that a book would have been written about it. It seems unlikely that the book could have been any better than this one, however.<br /><br />Definitely recommended.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12915625956942247343" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


