<div id="review_196399414" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/196399414" />
    <a title="Noah" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/635524-noah"><img alt="Noah" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1594956440p2/635524.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/196399414?book_show_action=true">Aug 09, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Noah" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Noah" href="/user/show/635524-noah">Noah</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780805089646" href="/book/show/6387913-pedro-and-me">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer196399414" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7981087770055055985">A little simple in its telling, and a little message-oriented, but I still liked it. It made me cry (which isn&apos;t saying much, as I recently cried over an episode of Restaurant: Impossible); there&apos;s always something about a death that is written honestly in some way or another, where the characters face it and the author shares it. I suppose, for me, it helps me connect with the characters as well as myself, and there&apos;s a relief in connecting with something rather than avoiding it. </span>
  <span id="freeText7981087770055055985" style="display:none">A little simple in its telling, and a little message-oriented, but I still liked it. It made me cry (which isn't saying much, as I recently cried over an episode of Restaurant: Impossible); there's always something about a death that is written honestly in some way or another, where the characters face it and the author shares it. I suppose, for me, it helps me connect with the characters as well as myself, and there's a relief in connecting with something rather than avoiding it. </span>
  <a data-text-id="7981087770055055985" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


